	(28,'contracts','28. Is FRUSTRATION OF PURPOSE a defense?','<p>Under contract law, if the parties enter into a contract <b>knowing </b>that the <b>failure of some condition</b> beyond their control will <b>deny one of the parties</b> the benefit of the bargain, that condition is an<b> implied material condition</b> of the contract, the failure of which <b>excuses both parties</b> from the agreement.</p><p>Here ... because ... therefore ...</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2017-09-24 18:18:32',1),
	(29,'contracts','29. Is MUTUAL MISTAKE a defense?','<p>Under <b>PEERLESS </b>when <b>both parties</b> enter into a contract because of <b>misunderstanding </b>as to a <b>material fact</b>, there is no \"meeting of the minds\" and the contract is void from the beginning.\r\n</p><p>\r\nHere .. because ... Therefore...</p>',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2017-09-24 18:12:51',1),
